<br>
And I admit, there is a certain amount of jealosy involved with the fact that not only could they FD escape from situations that would be deadly for a Warrior.  Not only could they FD pull in situations that a Warrior couldn't.  Not only could they do considerably more damage than a Warrior.  Not only could they tank in a pinch and seemingly do just as well as a Warrior.  But they could also, as a class in large numbers, solo circles around a Warrior.<br>
<br>
Now, you want to tell me that none of this matters and it's hunky dorry.  I'm dubious.  I want to feel I get as much out of my play time as the next person.  I want to feel that my character class is as useful and desired.  Yet unless I'm tanking, people have no real incentive to include me or my class.  Not so Mr. Monk.  If he isn't tanking he can be doing some whoop ass damage (certainly better than mine, by a long shot).  He can FD pull.  Maybe not as useful as it once was, but still a hell of a lot more than I can do.  So the absolutely last thing I want to see is that Monks are also tanking and tanking well.<br>
<br>
Anything short of it being reasonable to replace a Warrior with a Monk for tanking is relatively okay in my eyes.  I'd prefer that if they are going to allow Monks to viably solo in large numbers, they also allowed that option to Warriors, but I'm not holding my breath.  But as soon as it becomes clear that Monks are able to replace a Warrior for tanking and the group as a whole suffers no real detrimental down time or consequences as a result, is when you'll see me getting my tidy whities in a wad. <p>The Man in Black: We are men of action, lies do not become us. <br>
